# Linux Fundamentals

Below are the Linux fundamentals I have encountered and studied so far.

1. Navigation
The filesystem is a tree. You start at / (root).

pwd        --> printing working directory
ls         --> list files in current directory
ls -la     --> list all files with details + hidden files
cd /etc    --> change to /etc directory
cd ..      --> go up one level
cd ~       --> go to your home directory
cd -       --> go back to previous directory
tree /etc  --> show directory tree visually

2. Files
Creating, copying, moving, viewing and searching files

---Create & Manage---
touch file.txt         --> create an empty file
mkdir myfolder         --> create a directory
cp file.txt backup.txt --> copy a file
mv file.txt /tmp/      --> move or rename a file
rm file.txt            --> delete a file
rm -rf myfolder        --> delete folder recursively

---Read & Search---
cat file.txt          --> print file contents
less file.txt         --> scroll through a file (q to quit)
head -n 20 file.txt   --> show first 20 lines
grep "error" file.txt --> search for text inside a file
find / -name "*.conf" --> find files by name

3. Permission

ls -l file.txt --> view permissions 

4. Users
Understanding users, groups, and sudo is essential for privilege escalation

whoami                 --> show current user
id                     --> show user ID, group ID, and groups
who                    --> show who is logged in
sudo command           --> run command as root
sudo su                --> switch to root shell
adduser alice          --> create a new user
usermod -aG sudo alice --> add alice to sudo group
passwd alice           --> set user password
cat /etc/passwd        --> list all users on the system
cat /etc/shadow        --> hashed passwords (root only)
